@node INSTALLATION "Installation"

@{b}@{u}INSTALLATION@{uu}@{ub}


The installation is manual, I do not know how to write installations that will directly modify
the Golded Registry. However manual installation is straightforward involving only two steps,
@{"copying the files" link CopyFiles} and then @{"setting up Golded" link SetUP}.
Some basic knowledge of using a file manager such as Directory Opus or using the Shell will help.


@endnode
@node COPYFILES "CopyFiles"

@{b}@{u}Copying the necessary Files.@{uu}@{ub}

All the files you need are in the @{fg shine}Files@{fg text} folder of the main archive.

@{LIndent 2}
STEP ONE

First of all you need to create a directory called @{fg shine}HBasic2@{fg text} in @{fg shine}Golded:add-ons@{fg text}.
It does not need an icon but there is no harm if one is created. Copy both the @{fg shine}api@{fg text} and @{fg shine}syntax@{fg text}
folders from this archive to @{fg shine}Golded:add-ons/HBasic2@{fg text}.

Note: The @{fg shine}API@{fg text} folder does NOT contain the following three files as they are part of the Golded
distribution and cannot be distributed separately. You can need to copy them to the @{fg shine}HBasic2/api@{fg text}
folder.
If you do not have a C type environment already installed, you will need to install one, copy
the three files to HBasic2/api and then uninstall the C environment if it is no longer
required.

The three files needed are:
     @{fg fill}explorer.api
     mirror.api
     quickinfo.api@{fg text}

Note. Experienced users may not need to copy these files but access them directly from their
current path if a C type environment is already in use.

Note2. Do NOT copy @{fg fill}explorer.config@{fg text} from the C++ distribution but use the one
provided in this archive in the @{fg shine}api@{fg text} folder.


STEP TWO

No more directories need to be created but make use of existing folders in the Golded: assign.

Copy @{fg shine}Scanner/HBasic2@{fg text} from this archive to @{fg shine}Golded:etc/scanner@{fg text}

Copy the three files from @{fg shine}Presets@{fg text} in this archive to @{fg shine}Golded:etc/registry/presets@{fg text}



--------------------------------------

@{"List of files contained in the archive" link FileList}


@endnode
@node FILELIST "FileList"
The following files are provided in this archive.


@{b}@{u}1. The Documents folder.@{uu}@{ub}

    This guide and supporting images.



@{b}@{u}2. The Files Folder@{uu}@{ub}

@{fg shine}API@{fg text} folder

    @{fg fill}explorer.config@{fg text}     -   Configuration file for the explorer.api
    @{fg fill}os3.basic@{fg text}           -   Configuration file for the quickinfo.api

Note the following are needed but not provided due to copyright reasons.
    @{fg fill}mirror.api
    explorer.api
    quickinfo.api@{fg text}

@{fg shine}SYNTAX@{fg text} folder

    @{fg fill}Compiler
    Functions
    OS_Constants'x'@{fg text} (five files 1 to 5)
    @{fg fill}OS_Functions
    OS_Subs
    Special
    Statements@{fg text}

These are the Dictionary Files, plain ascii text files that are used by the Generic Parser to
highlight different types of keywords.

@{fg shine}SCANNER@{fg text} folder

    @{fg fill}HBasic2@{fg text}

@{fg shine}PRESETS@{fg text} folder.

    @{fg fill}hbasic.api
    hbasic.syntax
    hbasic.misc@{fg text}

These files are used to @{"set up" link SetUP} the new HBasic filetype in Golded.

@{fg shine}SCRIPTS@{fg text} folder

Contains two @{"Arexx scripts" link ArexxScripts} to create dictionary files for third party HBasic2 libraries.
These are tools and not needed to use the environment and can be copied anywhere the user wishes.

@endnode
@node SETUP "SetUP"

Setting Up Golded for the HBasic2 Environment.

Firstly ensure that the necessary @{"files have been copied" link CopyFiles} from the archive to the correct places
in the Golded: directory and that you have access to the Golded: C type API files.


Run Golded and select @{fg shine}Customise@{fg text} from the @{fg shine}Extras@{fg text} menu.
Highlight @{fg shine}Filetypes@{fg text} and click the PLUS icon, a new filetype called @{fg shine}Unnamed@{fg text} will appear.
Rename this using a @{"linger-click" link Glossary} rather than a normal double mouse click, change the name to
something meaningful such as @{fg shine}HBasic2@{fg text}.

Click the small + sign next to @{fg shine}HBasic2@{fg text} and you will see 2 folders, @{fg shine}Configuration@{fg text} and @{fg shine}Activation@{fg text}.


@{b}@{u}Setting the Activation.@{uu}@{ub}

Highlight Activation and once more click the PLUS icon. Linger Click the text that appears for the
new entry and enter the text "(#?.bas|#?.bh|#?.bc|BASIC)" without the quotes. This will enable
Golded to recognise HBasic files or change the filetype by typing BASIC in the Properties filetype
 entry.


@{b}@{u}Setting the Configuration.@{uu}@{ub}



@{b}@{u}1. Plug Ins@{uu}@{ub}

Highlight the @{fg shine}Configuration@{fg text} folder and click the PLUS icon. Golded's Pool requester will appear.

Click the small + next to @{fg shine}Plug-ins@{fg text}, there should be an entry @{fg shine}hbasic.api@{fg text}, if not then ensure all
@{"files have been copied" link CopyFiles} correctly  to @{fg shine}Golded:etc/registry/presets@{fg text}. Highlight @{fg shine}hbasic.api@{fg text} and click
on the OK icon. An entry Plug-ins will appear below. Double click this and there should be three
entries for the available plugins. These will read:

@{fg fill}golded:add-ons/hbasic2/api/explorer.api
golded:add-ons/habsic2/api/mirror.api
golded:add-ons/hbasic2/api/quickinfo.api@{fg text}

Note. Advanced users can linger-click to change the above paths to look at existing API files in
say a C++ file if they wish to save disk space.

Double click the path for explorer.api and the config entry should read
@{fg fill}CONFIG="golded:add-ons/hbasic2/api/explorer.config"@{fg text} do not change this.

Double click the mirror.api path and the config entry should be blank. Leave this.

Double click the quickinfo.api path and the entry should read
@{fg fill}golded:add-ons/hbasic2/api/os3.basic@{fg text} do not change this.

Click the SAVE to store the api@plugin settings.

If not proceeding to setting up the Syntax settings immediately then click the next SAVE button.
It is probably best to continue with the next stage.

@{b}@{u}2. Syntax@{uu}@{ub}

Highlight the @{fg shine}Configuration@{fg text} folder and click the PLUS icon. Golded's Pool requester will appear.

Click the small + next to @{fg shine}Syntax Highlighting@{fg text}, there should be an entry @{fg shine}hbasic.syntax@{fg text}, if not
then ensure all @{"files have been copied" link CopyFiles} correctly  to @{fg shine}Golded:etc/registry/presets@{fg text}. Highlight
@{fg shine}hbasic.syntax@{fg text} and click on the OK icon. An entry Syntax will appear below. Double click this
and the Syntax window will appear.

The first option is where you set the colours for the various types of keyword as per normal
practice with Golded. There should be 10 entries,

There is no sample page provided as this is not available for the Generic parser which the HBasic
environment uses.

Click the Details icon and the window changes to show how the parser is setup. Now click the
button marked Details.

Users with low memory or slower CPUs may wish to delete one or more of the OS_Constants dictionary
files. These have been arranged so that OS_Constants1 contains keywords for the OS most likely to
be used in an HBasic programme and  OS_Constants5 has keywords unlikely to be used.

To delete a dictionary click the small plus next to OS_Constants and you will see the 5 dictionary
files, highlight the one to delete and click on the X button.

Click OK and then on the SAVE to save the Syntax settings.


@{u}3. Folding@{uu}

Highlight the @{fg shine}Configuration@{fg text} folder and click the PLUS icon. Golded's Pool requester will appear.

Click the small + next to @{fg shine}Miscellaneous@{fg text}, there should be an entry @{fg shine}hbasic.misc@{fg text}
Highlight @{fg shine}hbasic.misc@{fg text} and click on the OK icon. An entry Miscellaneous will appear below. There
is no need to make any further corrections. Click OK and then on the SAVE to save the Misc
settings.

Click the next SAVE button and the  HBasic2 environment setup is completed.

@endnode








@node AREXXSCRIPTS "ARexx Scripts"

@{Lindent 1}
Two arexx scripts are supplied to create Golded Dictionary files for using third party HiSoft
Basic library calls. The first script is @{fg shine}HB_Functions.rexx@{fg text} which scans for *.bh files and creates
a file in Ram: called @{fg shine}Functions@{fg text} and one called @{fg shine}Subs@{fg text}. The second script is @{fg shine}HB_Constants.rexx@{fg text}
which scans for *.bc files and creates a file in ram: called @{fg shine}Constants@{fg text}.

These can be copied to Golded:etc/syntax/HBasic2 from where they can be added to Golded's
Dictionaries. It is best to rename these to specific names like @{fg shine}My_Functions@{fg text} etc.

The scripts work on @{b}all@{ub} the *.bh and *.bc files in a given directory so do not use the HBasic/BH
directory or you may be in for quite a wait while all the files are processed. The best way is
to copy the third party *bh and *bc files into a clean directory, ram: would be perfect, and then
run the scripts.

The syntax to use is "@{fg fill}rx scriptname directory@{fg text}" eg. rx HB_Functions.rexx ram: will create a Subs
file and a Functions file for any *.bh files in ram:

@endnode
@node GLOSSARY "Glossary"

Linger Click.

Golded uses this rather strange way of selecting text items in order to edit them. A double click
is normally used to enter parameters or in some cases has no function. The linger click is a
single click followed by another single click after a short period. If you find that you have
difficulty, either nothing happens or a double click is detected instead then alter the workbench
Input preferences and reduce the time delay for the double click.

@endnode
@node HINTS "Hints and Tips"
@{fg shine}@{b}Hints and Tips@{ub} @{fg text}

This environment for Golded will work without paying attention to the following but may not be at
its best.


@{u}@{fg shine}Use nice fonts@{fg text}@{uu}
A small font is best for use with the explorer. This can be edited in the @{fg fill}explorer.config@{fg text} file.
It is currently set up to use @{fg fill}XHelvetica.font size 9@{fg text} which most users will have already. If the
font in the config file is not found then Golded uses the same font used for the text display. I
actually use @{fg fill}tny.font size 8@{fg text} which can be found on Aminet.



@{u}@{fg shine}Programming Style@{fg text}@{uu}

There are a few things that need to be adhered to to make the environment highlight things
properly. NOTE. These will NOT have any affect on the HiSoft Basic programme itself. It will
only affect the way Golded displays the text.

@{u}1. Variables.@{uu}

In HiSoft Basic you can have variables A% and A& etc which are different entities. If the
qualifier is omitted then a variable A will be of the type defined in the programme such as
DEF INT A-Z or explicitly as a constant in a header file. I originally did not include the &
symbol in the words highlighted from the OS header files but then decided as a similar variable
with a % or $ sign would also be highlighted, decided that only variables as exactly defined in
the header files would get highlighted. So make sure that when using functions, sub programmes
and constants for the Amiga OS that you do include the type qualifier. This will not affect your
code at all but will affect whether an OS call is marked as such in Golded. It does also
encourage better programming practice by ensuring that variables always have the type qualifier
and avoids confusion.

I doubt anyone would decide to define a variable GT_Underscore% which would be similar to the OS
constant GT_Underscore& and then rely on chance to use GT_Underscore and pick up the one which
was defined first. However even in the HiSoft Basic examples variables are used that are identical
in name to some OS constants if they were used !


@{u}2. Comments and Compiler Options.@{uu}

In HiSoft Basic, you can use both REM and ' to comment out lines.

The first generic parser for Golded would only let you use one item, I chose the ' to highlight
comments. Later versions of Golded will now (at my request) let you define more than one word to
define a single line comment. However I chose to just restrict highlighting comments just to the
' symbol. There is a reason for limiting to just the one method.

HiSoft Basic has compiler options that are a comment followed by a keyword beginning with a $
symbol. I wanted to highlight compiler options. If they begin with a ' symbol then they will
be shown as a @{"comment" link comments.jpg/main} but if they start @{"REM " link comments.jpg/main}then the
associated compiler keywords are shown as such.

So although it makes no difference to your Basic code it is best to use ' for comments and REM for
defining compiler options. It does not matter if you do not stick to this but the highlighting in
Golded will not be as useful as it could.


@{u}3. Comments and Folding.@{uu}

Golded lets you fold subroutines etc into a single line.
I did think of using something like @{b}' FOLD @{ub} for this but decided to use what most people may have
as comments anyway. It is of course possible to change the folding string to suit your own needs but it
MUST be in the form of a comment so it is transparent to HiSoft Basic.

The fold symbol now for both starting and ending folds is @{b}'***@{ub} as similar comments are often used
at the beginning of routines for clarity anyway. Note that @{b}' *** @{ub}will not work but it is easy to
do a global replace in Golded if you want to use the folding feature. Note the latter is useful for
displaying comments outwith any folded structures. See @{"Example1" link Folded.jpg/main} and @{"Example2" link Unfolded.jpg/main}

@endnode





